    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-17T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-17T05:00:00-05:00" n="407"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">340.1115A/2029: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Hungary</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Budapest</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-17T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 17, 1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received June 17—9:27 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>358. Referring to my telegram 330, May 3 [<hi rend="italic">31</hi>] 5 p.m.,<note
                        n="9" xml:id="d407fn9">Not printed.</note> concerning transit visas through
                    Germany of American citizen refugees from Yugoslavia and also Americans from
                    Hungary who desire to return to the United States. From information received
                    from the Embassy at Berlin and from the attitude of the German Legation here it
                    appears that there is small probability of such visas being granted unless the
                    Department exerts pressure upon the German Embassy at Washington.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Pell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
